data.name: Contains Number
data.description:
We say a nonnegative integer `$k$` is contained in a nonnegative integer `$n$` when the digits of `$k$` appear in the digits of `$n$` in order when read from left to right. For example,

If `$n=102030405$`, then `$n$` contains `$12, 123, 1203, 120405, \ldots$`, for example. Keep in mind that every integer contains `$0$`, since `$0$` technically has no digits.

Write a function `contains` that takes in two integers `$n$` and `$k$` and determines whether `$n$` contains `$k$`, outputting `True` if `$n$` contains `$k$` and `False` if otherwise.

Sample Inputs:

`contains(1000001, 11) = True`

`contains(12345, 53) = False` (Note that `$12345$` contains the digits of `$53$`, but out of order.)

`contains(1, 2) = False`

`contains(12345, 135) = True`

Input Information:

`$0\leq n, k\leq 10^{100}$`
